# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bernard-budiansky
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] A significant part of **aeronautical science** is a branch of dynamics called aerodynamics, which deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Attempts to fly without any real aeronautical understanding have been made from the earliest times, typically by constructing wings and jumping from a tower with crippling or lethal results.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Wiser investigators sought to gain some rational understanding through the study of bird flight.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Medieval Islamic Golden Age scientists such as Abbas ibn Firnas also made such studies.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The founders of modern aeronautics, Leonardo da Vinci in the Renaissance and Cayley in 1799, both began their investigations with studies of bird flight.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Man-carrying kites are believed to have been used extensively in ancient China.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] In 1282 the Italian explorer Marco Polo described the Chinese techniques then current.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The Chinese also constructed small hot air balloons, or lanterns, and rotary-wing toys.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] An early European to provide any scientific discussion of flight was Roger Bacon, who described principles of operation for the lighter-than-air balloon and the flapping-wing ornithopter, which he envisaged would be constructed in the future.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The lifting medium for his balloon would be an "aether" whose composition he did not know.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] In the late fifteenth century, Leonardo da Vinci followed up his study of birds with designs for some of the earliest flying machines, including the flapping-wing ornithopter and the rotating-wing helicopter.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Although his designs were rational, they were not based on particularly good science.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Many of his designs, such as a four-person screw-type helicopter, have severe flaws.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Da Vinci's work was lost after his death and did not reappear until it had been overtaken by the work of George Cayley.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The modern era of lighter-than-air flight began early in the 17th century with Galileo's experiments in which he showed that air has weight.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Around 1650 Cyrano de Bergerac wrote some fantasy novels in which he described the principle of ascent using a substance (dew) he supposed to be lighter than air, and descending by releasing a controlled amount of the substance.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Francesco Lana de Terzi measured the pressure of air at sea level and in 1670 proposed the first scientifically credible lifting medium in the form of hollow metal spheres from which all the air had been pumped out.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] These would be lighter than the displaced air and able to lift an airship.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] His proposed methods of controlling height are still in use today; by carrying ballast which may be dropped overboard to gain height, and by venting the lifting containers to lose height.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] In practice de Terzi's spheres would have collapsed under air pressure, and further developments had to wait for more practicable lifting gases.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] From the mid-18th century the Montgolfier brothers in France began experimenting with balloons.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Their balloons were made of paper, and early experiments using steam as the lifting gas were short-lived due to its effect on the paper as it condensed.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Meanwhile, the discovery of hydrogen led Joseph Black in c.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] 1780 to propose its use as a lifting gas, though practical demonstration awaited a gas-tight balloon material.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] On hearing of the Montgolfier Brothers' invitation, the French Academy member Jacques Charles offered a similar demonstration of a hydrogen balloon.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Charles and two craftsmen, the Robert brothers, developed a gas-tight material of rubberised silk for the envelope.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The hydrogen gas was to be generated by chemical reaction during the filling process.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The Montgolfier designs had several shortcomings, not least the need for dry weather and a tendency for sparks from the fire to set light to the paper balloon.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The manned design had a gallery around the base of the balloon rather than the hanging basket of the first, unmanned design, which brought the paper closer to the fire.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] On their free flight, De Rozier and d'Arlandes took buckets of water and sponges to douse these fires as they arose.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] On the other hand, the manned design of Charles was essentially modern.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] As a result of these exploits, the hot air balloon became known as the *Montgolfière* type and the gas balloon the *Charlière*.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Charles and the Robert brothers' next balloon, *La Caroline*, was a Charlière that followed Jean Baptiste Meusnier's proposals for an elongated dirigible balloon, and was notable for having an outer envelope with the gas contained in a second, inner ballonet.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] On 19 September 1784, it completed the first flight of over 100 kilometres (62 mi), between Paris and Beuvry, despite the man-powered propulsive devices proving useless.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The balloon envelope was made of goldbeater's skin.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The first flight ended in disaster and the approach has seldom been used since.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Sir George Cayley (1773–1857) is widely acknowledged as the founder of modern aeronautics.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] He was first called the "father of the aeroplane" in 1846 and Henson called him the "father of aerial navigation." He was the first true scientific aerial investigator to publish his work, which included for the first time the underlying principles and forces of flight.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] In 1809 he began the publication of a landmark three-part treatise titled "On Aerial Navigation" (1809–1810).
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] He developed the modern conventional form of the fixed-wing aeroplane having a stabilising tail with both horizontal and vertical surfaces, flying gliders both unmanned and manned.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] He introduced the use of the whirling arm test rig to investigate the aerodynamics of flight, using it to discover the benefits of the curved or cambered aerofoil over the flat wing he had used for his first glider.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] He also identified and described the importance of dihedral, diagonal bracing and drag reduction, and contributed to the understanding and design of ornithopters and parachutes.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Another significant invention was the tension-spoked wheel, which he devised in order to create a light, strong wheel for aircraft undercarriage.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] During the 19th century, Cayley's ideas were further developed, tested, and formalised.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Public and scientific interest in aeronautics grew during the Victorian era, with notable contributions from figures such as John Stringfellow, James Glaisher, Francis Wenham, and Frederick Brearey.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Wenham, Glaisher, and Brearey co-founded the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain in 1866, together with the 8th Duke of Argyll.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Although aeronautical research at the time remained largely experimental, the Society played an important role in promoting heavier-than-air flight, including through the First Aeronautical Exhibition held in 1868 at The Crystal Palace.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] These developments, along with growing international interest, helped lay the groundwork for the later work of Horatio Phillips among others, but more importantly of Otto Lilienthal, a German engineer and businessman who became known as the "flying man".
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] He was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favourably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] His work led to the development of the modern wing.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] His flight attempts in Berlin in the year 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the "Lilienthal Normalsegelapparat" is considered to be the first air plane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Otto Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Aeronautics may be divided into three main branches, Aviation, Aeronautical science and Aeronautical engineering.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Aviation is the art or practice of aeronautics.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Historically aviation meant only heavier-than-air flight, but nowadays it includes flying in balloons and airships.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Aeronautical engineering covers the design and construction of aircraft, including how they are powered, how they are used and how they are controlled for safe operation.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] A major part of aeronautical engineering is aerodynamics, the science of passing through the air.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] With the increasing activity in space flight, nowadays aeronautics and astronautics are often combined as aerospace engineering.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] The science of aerodynamics deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] A rocket or rocket vehicle is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle which obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] In all rockets, the exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Rocket engines push rockets forwards simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology of the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Rockets are used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight and exploration of other planets.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, they are very lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Chemical rockets are the most common type of rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:bernard-budiansky/aeronautical] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:bernard-budiansky/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:bernard-budiansky/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:bernard-budiansky/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:bernard-budiansky/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:bernard-budiansky/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:bernard-budiansky/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:bernard-budiansky/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:bernard-budiansky/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] Budiansky was born in New York City on March 8, 1925, to Russian immigrant parents, Louis and Rose (Chaplick) Budiansky.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] Upon obtaining a Bachelor of Civil Engineering degree from City College of New York in 1944 when he was barely over 19, he became an aeronautical research scientist at the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA, forerunner to NASA) at Langley Field, Virginia.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He took an educational leave from NACA to enroll in 1947 in the graduate program in applied mathematics at Brown University, completing his Ph.D. in 1950 with a dissertation entitled *Fundamental Theorems and Consequences of the Slip Theory of Plasticity*.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He returned to Langley in 1950 and, in 1952, was appointed Head of the Structural Mechanics Branch.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He joined the faculty of Harvard in 1955.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He made widely cited contributions on the way that fissures and joints in rocks affect the propagation of seismic waves, which has become a standard basis for inferring rock properties in the Earth, and contributed to understanding stressing and deformation in the inflation of the human lung.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] His work of the later years was focused on problems in the domain of materials science, explaining mechanical properties of solids in terms of microscopic mechanisms.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He referred to this important area as "micromechanics".
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He was one of its pioneers, and contributed to explanation of the fracture of ductile metals and the toughening of normally brittle ceramics and composite materials.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] Budiansky won many honors including the AIAA 1970 Dryden Research Lecturer; CCNY 1974 Townsend Harris Medal; ASCE 1982 von Karman Medal; Society of Engineering Science 1985 Eringen Medal; ASME 1989 Timoshenko Medal.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He received honorary doctorates from Northwestern University 1986 and Technion Israel Institute of Technology.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] In addition he was a member of the National Academy of Sciences, the National Academy of Engineering, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences; the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences; and the Danish Center for Applied Mathematics and Mechanics.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] Professional affiliations included: ASCE, ASME, AIAA, and AGU.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] Bernard Budiansky died January 23, 1999, at his home in Lexington, Massachusetts, aged 73.
[src:bernard-budiansky/bernard-budiansky] He was survived by his wife and two sons, one of whom is writer Stephen Budiansky.
